                            <comment id="484867" author="adilger" created="Wed, 21 Jan 2026 20:07:25 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The most common source of failure that I&apos;ve seen is in test-framework.sh due to the use of &lt;tt&gt;${fsname}_CREATED_POOLS&lt;/tt&gt; causing:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;test-framework.sh: line 9303: 56af3883_CREATED_POOLS: bad substitution
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;because bash does not allow variable names to start with a digit.  This can be easily fixed in the &lt;tt&gt;test-frameworks.h&lt;/tt&gt; code, but is not retroactive to all old versions/branches, so it would be better to constrain Autotest to set a filesystem name that does not start with a digit.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Something like &lt;tt&gt;FSNAME=fRND7HEX&lt;/tt&gt; or maybe &lt;tt&gt;FSNAME=fsRND6HX&lt;/tt&gt; to ensure the whole name cannot be translated as a hex number (not sure if that makes a difference or not, but not harmful).  With &lt;tt&gt;16^6=2^24=16M&lt;/tt&gt; filesystem names that should still be enough to avoid collisions for concurrent filesystem names (about 2^12 = 1/4096 chance of two random 24-bit names colliding).  Given that only ~300-400 test sessions are running at one time, maybe double that overlapping at any one time, the risk is low.  Autotest could &quot;allocate&quot; unique filesystem names instead of purely random names to avoid name re-use for a long period of time to entirely avoid the chance of collision.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="484850" author="adilger" created="Wed, 21 Jan 2026 19:11:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It turns out that this failure (and several others) was triggered by running the test sessions with a random &lt;tt&gt;FSNAME&lt;/tt&gt; set for each one. It isn&apos;t clear why this particular subtest was failing, because nothing in the test itself is referencing &lt;tt&gt;FSNAME&lt;/tt&gt; directly (though indirectly via &lt;tt&gt;$DIR=$MOUNT/$testname&lt;/tt&gt;, and &lt;tt&gt;$MOUNT=/mnt/$FSNAME&lt;/tt&gt;, but that would be constant during the whole subtest. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
